        'title' => 'Mt. Pinatubo Crater Hike: A Day Plan from Capas, Tarlac',
        'slug' => 'mt-pinatubo-crater-day-hike-capas-tarlac',
        'excerpt' => 'The Pinatubo crater day hike from Capas is one of the easier big-volcano walks in Luzon. Here is the 4x4 route, the trek, and what to pack.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Pinatubo is the volcano everyone in Luzon knows from the 1991 eruption, and the crater lake it left behind is now one of the most rewarding day hikes you can do within a four-hour drive of Manila. The trip starts at the Capas tourism office in Tarlac, where you transfer to a 4x4 jeep for the ride across the old lahar fields, then walk the last stretch up to the crater rim.</p>
<p>This is a real day hike, not a casual stroll, but it is friendly for first-timers if you go in dry season and start early. Tara, here is the practical kwento.</p>
<h2>Booking the Trip</h2>
<p>The Capas tourism office in barangay Sta. Juliana is the official starting point. You can book a 4x4 and guide combo on arrival, but on weekends and holidays the queue gets long, so call ahead through the office number listed on the <a href="https://capas.gov.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Capas municipal site</a> or arrange through a registered tour operator from Manila that handles the van transfer too.</p>
<h3>What the Package Covers</h3>
<p>The standard arrangement includes the 4x4 ride for up to five people, the guide fee, and the environmental fee. You pay separately for lunch and for the optional bath at the small spring near the trailhead. Bring small bills, the office and the trailhead vendors do not accept cards.</p>
<h2>The 4x4 Ride</h2>
<p>The ride across the lahar plains takes around an hour and a half each way. The terrain is gray volcanic ash carved by years of rain into shallow rivers and sand bars. The 4x4 splashes through the streams, climbs over loose gravel, and crosses dry beds where the wind kicks up white dust. Goggles or sunglasses help, and a light bandana over the nose makes the dustier sections more tolerable.</p>
<h3>Photo Stops</h3>
<p>The drivers know the spots where the lahar canyons form natural amphitheaters, and most will pause for a quick photo if you ask politely. The most dramatic stretch is the upper canyon about an hour in, where the walls rise on both sides and the river curves through the gray.</p>
<h2>The Trek to the Crater</h2>
<p>From the trailhead it is around a 30 to 45 minute walk up a stone path. The grade is gentle for the first stretch, then climbs more steeply near the top. The path is well maintained with handrails on the exposed sections, but trekking poles still help if your knees complain on descents.</p>
<h3>The Crater Lake</h3>
<p>The view at the top opens onto the crater lake, which sits in the caldera the eruption left behind. The water is a turquoise blue from the dissolved minerals, ringed by ridges of black volcanic rock. Swimming is no longer allowed because the lake has become more acidic over the years, but a viewing platform lets you sit for as long as you want. Pack a sandwich and eat it there.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Closed shoes with grip, the path is dusty and the descent is loose</li>
    <li>Sunglasses or goggles for the 4x4 dust</li>
    <li>A bandana or light buff for the nose and mouth</li>
    <li>At least two liters of water, the trailhead has only one small store</li>
    <li>Sunscreen, a hat, and a light long-sleeve, there is no shade on the lahar plains</li>
    <li>A power bank, the ride drains phones fast from the photos</li>
    <li>Cash in small bills for fees and lunch</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Capas</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> or Genesis bus bound for Iba or Sta. Cruz, Zambales and ask the driver to drop you at the Capas junction. From there, a tricycle to the tourism office takes around 20 minutes. If you have a car, the SCTEX exit at Capas puts you 15 minutes from the office.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The trail closes during the rainy season, usually from June to October, because the lahar rivers flood and the 4x4 cannot cross. The best months are November to May, with December to February being the coolest. Avoid weekends if you can, the crater platform gets crowded by 10 a.m.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Most travelers do Pinatubo as a day trip from Manila. If you want to break the ride, stay one night in Clark or Angeles and leave at 4 a.m. for the 5:30 a.m. trail call time. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298459-Angeles_City_Pampanga_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Clark is closer to the SCTEX exit for an early departure.</p>
<p>The crater holds up even on the second visit. Start before sunrise, respect the dust, and let the lahar do the work.</p>
