        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bolinao is the western tip of Pangasinan that most Manila travelers reach by overnight bus. The town itself is small, but the coastline strings together half a dozen beaches, a lighthouse, two waterfalls, and a giant clam sanctuary, which is enough for a slow two-night plan. The most photographed beach is Patar with its tan-white sand, and the easier swim beach is Tara closer to town.</p>
<p>This is the calm first-timer read. No resort pricing, just the practical layout.</p>
<h2>Getting to Bolinao</h2>
<p>From Manila, <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> runs the direct bus from Cubao and Pasay to Bolinao town proper. The ride is around six to seven hours including a short stop at the Tarlac station. Five Star Bus also runs the route. Tickets are cheaper if you book on a weekday and avoid the long-weekend departures.</p>
<h3>Driving Option</h3>
<p>If you drive, the route is NLEX to SCTEX to TPLEX, exit at Urdaneta, then take the McArthur Highway and the Alaminos road. Total drive time is around five hours in light traffic. Gas up in Alaminos because the stations between there and Bolinao are limited.</p>
<h2>The Beach Order</h2>
<p>The accommodations cluster either in Patar, around 30 minutes from town, or along the road between Bolinao and Patar. Pick your base depending on what you want.</p>
<h3>Patar Beach</h3>
<p>Patar is the long stretch of tan-white sand the brochures use. The waves are bigger here, which makes the swim livelier in dry season and the surf small but real in habagat months. The downside is the sand temperature at midday, the dark grains hold heat, so plan beach time for morning and late afternoon.</p>
<h3>Tara Beach and Town</h3>
<p>Tara is the quieter swim beach closer to the town center. The water is calmer, the sand is finer, and the beachfront has more food stalls. Good base if you have kids or you want to walk back to town for dinner.</p>
<h2>Side Trips Worth Doing</h2>
<p>Two nights is the right length because the side trips are spread out.</p>
<h3>Cape Bolinao Lighthouse</h3>
<p>The white lighthouse on Punta Piedra has been guiding boats since 1905 and is one of the highest in the country at 107 meters above sea level. The climb to the viewing deck is short and the wind off the bay is real. Sunset here is the standard closing for a Bolinao day. Bring a windbreaker.</p>
<h3>Bolinao Falls</h3>
<p>There are three Bolinao Falls along the road inland from town. Falls 1 is the most developed with a small swimming pool, Falls 2 is the prettiest, and Falls 3 is the quietest. A tricycle from town can shuttle you to all three in a half day.</p>
<h3>Enchanted Cave</h3>
<p>The Enchanted Cave is a small natural pool inside a limestone chamber. The entrance fee is low, you change into swimwear, and you swim in the freshwater spring. Go early before the tour vans arrive at midday.</p>
<h3>Giant Clam Sanctuary</h3>
<p>The Bolinao Marine Laboratory in Lucero runs the giant clam sanctuary you can snorkel during low tide. The shells are massive and the marine biologists are happy to explain the breeding program. Bring your own snorkel gear or rent at the entrance.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Reef-safe sunscreen, a wide hat, and a rashguard</li>
    <li>Slippers and aqua shoes for the rocky stretches near the falls</li>
    <li>Cash, the ATMs in Bolinao town can run out on long weekends</li>
    <li>A light jacket for the lighthouse and the bus ride home</li>
    <li>Insect repellent for the falls and the cave</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where to Sleep</h2>
<p>You can compare guesthouses and beachfront options for both Patar and town on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7790937-Bolinao_Pangasinan_Province_Ilocos_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Patar is the better base for sunset, town is the better base for food and the falls.</p>
<p>Bolinao is the calm Pangasinan weekend Manila travelers underrate. Two nights is enough to do the lighthouse, the falls, the cave, and still nap on the beach.</p>
