    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2021/10/things-to-do-in-pangasinan-tourist-spots-itinerary.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Pangasinan Two-Day Road Loop: Beyond Hundred Islands',
        'slug' => 'pangasinan-two-day-loop-beyond-hundred-islands',
        'excerpt' => 'Hundred Islands gets the spotlight, but Pangasinan has a wider loop worth driving. Here is the two-day plan covering Manaoag, Dagupan, and the western coast.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Most Manila travelers see Pangasinan as a single stop, either Hundred Islands in Alaminos or Patar Beach in Bolinao. The province actually rewards a wider loop. With two days and a car, you can do Manaoag for the basilica, Dagupan for the bangus dinner, and the western coast for the beach the next morning, all without backtracking.</p>
<p>This is the calm road-trip read for a two-day Pangasinan plan that respects the distances.</p>
<h2>The Route in Order</h2>
<p>The loop starts at NLEX-SCTEX-TPLEX, exits at Urdaneta, then runs counterclockwise through Manaoag, Dagupan, Alaminos, and Bolinao before returning to Manila via the same TPLEX. The full drive is around 12 hours over two days, with the longest single stretch at three hours.</p>
<h3>Day 1: Urdaneta to Dagupan</h3>
<p>Leave Manila by 5 a.m. to dodge the toll-plaza queue at Balintawak. Exit at Urdaneta around 8 a.m., have a quick longganisa breakfast, then drive 30 minutes to the Minor Basilica of Our Lady of Manaoag. The church opens early and the parking is easier before 10 a.m. The Sunday crowds can stretch the visit to two hours, weekday visits are smoother.</p>
<p>From Manaoag, drive west to Dagupan for lunch. Dawel River Cruise is a calm one-hour ride if you want to slow down before the food. For dinner, the bangus places along the riverbank serve the local milkfish boneless and grilled. Matutina and Aling Tonya are two of the older names.</p>
<h3>Where to Sleep on Night 1</h3>
<p>Dagupan or Lingayen are the practical overnight stops. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g303329-Dagupan_City_Pangasinan_Province_Ilocos_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Lingayen is closer to the Veterans Memorial Beach if you want a sunset walk.</p>
<h3>Day 2: Alaminos to Bolinao</h3>
<p>Leave Dagupan by 7 a.m. and drive to Alaminos for the Hundred Islands National Park. Skip the longer boat tour and book the small bangka for three islands, which is enough for half a day. Governors Island has the viewing deck, Quezon Island has the swim area, and Marcos Island has the small cave.</p>
<p>After lunch, continue west to Bolinao. The drive is around 90 minutes. Visit Cape Bolinao Lighthouse for sunset, then catch the late evening bus or drive back via TPLEX. If you have the energy for the falls or the Enchanted Cave, add a third day in Bolinao.</p>
<h2>What to Eat Along the Way</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Manaoag: tupig and bibingka from the stalls near the basilica</li>
    <li>Dagupan: bangus, the local milkfish, served boneless and grilled</li>
    <li>Lingayen: pigar-pigar, a peppered beef stir-fry served with cabbage</li>
    <li>Alaminos: longganisa, the small garlicky kind</li>
    <li>Bolinao: binungey, a sticky rice cooked in bamboo</li>
</ul>
<h2>Driving Notes</h2>
<p>The full loop is around 380 kilometers from Manila and back. Gas up in Urdaneta on the way in and in Alaminos before the Bolinao stretch. The roads are paved and well marked, but the coastal stretch between Lingayen and Alaminos has slow sections through small towns. Watch for tricycles.</p>
<h2>If You Take the Bus Instead</h2>
<p>Without a car, the loop is harder. Better to pick one base for the weekend. <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> runs direct routes to Dagupan, Alaminos, and Bolinao from Cubao and Pasay. From any of these three towns, tricycles and jeeps cover the local sights.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May are the safest for the beach legs. Avoid the typhoon weeks from August to October because the western Pangasinan coast catches the wind. Manaoag is busiest on Wednesdays for the novena mass, so weekday-but-not-Wednesday is the sweet spot.</p>
<p>Two days in Pangasinan, one big loop, three different kinds of stops. The province is bigger than the Hundred Islands brochure suggests.</p>
