        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2022/01/best-bolinao-beach-resorts-pangasinan.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Cape Bolinao Lighthouse and Patar Sunset: A Slow Afternoon Plan',
        'slug' => 'cape-bolinao-lighthouse-patar-sunset-afternoon',
        'excerpt' => 'Cape Bolinao Lighthouse on Punta Piedra is the second highest in the country. Here is how to pair it with a Patar Beach sunset for the calmest Bolinao afternoon.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cape Bolinao Lighthouse has been guiding boats around the western tip of Pangasinan since 1905. It sits on Punta Piedra at around 107 meters above sea level, which makes it the second tallest lighthouse in the country after Cape Bojeador in Ilocos Norte. The structure is white, sun-bleached, and still active, with a small viewing deck around the lamp room that catches the wind off the South China Sea.</p>
<p>Paired with a sunset walk at Patar Beach, the lighthouse fills the late afternoon of a Bolinao weekend without rushing anything.</p>
<h2>Getting to the Lighthouse</h2>
<p>The lighthouse sits in Brgy. Patar, around 35 minutes from Bolinao town proper. If you drove in, the road is paved most of the way, with a short rough section near the entrance. Park at the lot below and walk up the short stone stairway to the base of the tower.</p>
<h3>Without a Car</h3>
<p>From town, a tricycle to the lighthouse and Patar Beach can be hired for a half day. The drivers wait, take you between the two stops, and bring you back to town for a flat rate. Settle the price at the start to avoid haggling later. Most accommodations along the road can arrange this.</p>
<h2>The Climb to the Top</h2>
<p>The caretaker opens the door to the lighthouse during daylight hours. The spiral staircase inside is narrow, the rails are old, and the climb is steep but short. The top opens onto a small circular deck around the lamp room. The view stretches across the bay to Cabarruyan Island and, on clear days, all the way to the tip of Anda. The wind here is strong year round, so hold your hat and your phone.</p>
<h3>Photo Notes</h3>
<p>The exterior of the lighthouse looks best in the late afternoon light around 4:30 p.m., when the white walls catch the warm tones. The interior is dim, so a phone camera struggles unless you have the night mode. The deck at the top works for both the inland view of Patar Beach and the seaward view at sunset.</p>
<h2>Patar Beach for Sunset</h2>
<p>From the lighthouse, the drive to the main Patar Beach is around five minutes. The beach is a long stretch of tan-white sand with a few clusters of food stalls and small guesthouses. Park anywhere along the access road and walk to the waterline.</p>
<h3>The Sunset Spot</h3>
<p>The center of the beach faces directly west, which is the obvious sunset angle. The southern end has a small rocky outcrop that frames the sun if you want a different photo. The northern end has the calmest water for a last swim before dark.</p>
<h3>What to Bring</h3>
<ul>
    <li>A light long-sleeve for the lighthouse wind</li>
    <li>A wide hat for the lighthouse climb</li>
    <li>Slippers and a beach towel for the Patar walk</li>
    <li>Insect repellent for the post-sunset hour</li>
    <li>A flashlight or phone light for the walk back to the car</li>
    <li>Cash for the lighthouse entrance and tricycle fare</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Eat Nearby</h2>
<p>The Patar Beach front has several light-material cantinas serving grilled fish, sinigang, and cold buko. Nothing fancy, just honest beach food. For a sit-down dinner, drive back to Bolinao town and try the beachside places near the public market for fresh kinilaw and grilled tuna.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May give the most reliable sunsets. The wet season from June to October has dramatic skies but also sudden squalls that can ruin a photo plan. The lighthouse closes when the wind is too strong, usually during typhoon weeks.</p>
<p>For places to sleep along the Patar road or in Bolinao town, compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7790937-Bolinao_Pangasinan_Province_Ilocos_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>One lighthouse, one beach, one slow afternoon. The Bolinao sunset earns the long drive.</p>
