    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 6. Pampanga 20 tourist spots
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2021/09/things-to-do-in-pampanga-tourist-spots-itinerary.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Pampanga in Two Days: A First-Timer Itinerary Beyond the Food',
        'slug' => 'pampanga-two-days-first-timer-itinerary-beyond-food',
        'excerpt' => 'Pampanga is the culinary capital, but the province also has historical churches, hot air balloons, and a calm bird sanctuary. Here is the two-day first-timer plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Pampanga gets called the culinary capital for good reason. The Kapampangan kitchen still defines a lot of Filipino fine-dining menus. But the province also holds historical churches from the Spanish era, a candaba bird sanctuary, the giant lanterns of San Fernando, and the Clark area which used to be the largest U.S. air base outside the mainland. A two-day plan gives you enough time to eat well and still see the rest.</p>
<p>This is the calm first-timer read.</p>
<h2>Day 1: San Fernando, Angeles, and the Food</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to the San Fernando exit. The drive is around 90 minutes in light traffic.</p>
<h3>Morning: Heritage Walk in San Fernando</h3>
<p>Start at the Metropolitan Cathedral of San Fernando, a Spanish-era church with a quiet courtyard. From there, walk to the Pampanga Provincial Capitol and the Heroes Hall, both within five minutes on foot. The Giant Lantern Museum sits a short tricycle ride away and is open year round, even outside the December festival.</p>
<h3>Lunch: A Sit-Down Kapampangan Meal</h3>
<p>Atching Lillian Borromeo in Mexico, Pampanga is the heritage cook the locals send food writers to. Bale Dutung in Angeles is the other big name, run by the late Claude Tayag's family. Both require advance booking. For walk-in, Aling Lucing in Angeles serves the original sisig the city is known for.</p>
<h3>Afternoon: Clark Walking Loop</h3>
<p>Drive to Clark Freeport and walk the old base streets. The flagpole, the parade ground, and the airfield grounds give a sense of the scale. The Air Force City Park has the static aircraft displays. The Korean Town area in Friendship has restaurants if you want a non-Kapampangan dinner.</p>
<h3>Night: Where to Sleep</h3>
<p>Angeles City has the widest range of hotels for the first night. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298459-Angeles_City_Pampanga_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Candaba, Bacolor, and Home</h2>
<p>Day two leans into the smaller towns south and east of San Fernando.</p>
<h3>Morning: Candaba Bird Sanctuary</h3>
<p>The Candaba wetlands are a Ramsar site that hosts thousands of migratory birds from October to March. Even outside the season, the rice fields and lily ponds are worth a slow drive. Bring binoculars if you have them. The site is reached via the Pulilan or Baliuag exits and the road through Apalit.</p>
<h3>Late Morning: San Guillermo Church in Bacolor</h3>
<p>The half-buried church is the visual reminder of the 1995 Pinatubo lahar that swallowed Bacolor. The original floor is around three meters below the current ground level, and the church reopened with the new floor at lahar height. The visit is short but memorable.</p>
<h3>Lunch: Mexican Town for the Aristocrat</h3>
<p>Atching Lillian's bibingka and the Sta. Rita restaurants in town serve the older sweets and dishes most Manila restaurants no longer make. San Nicolas pastries are the local pasalubong.</p>
<h3>Afternoon: Apalit and the Drive Home</h3>
<p>If you have energy, swing by Apalit for the San Pedro Apostol Church, then take NLEX back to Manila. The drive is around 90 minutes if you leave before the 4 p.m. tollgate crunch.</p>
<h2>What to Bring Home</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Sansrival from Razon's, the original Pampanga version</li>
    <li>Tibok-tibok, the Kapampangan carabao-milk dessert</li>
    <li>Tocino and longganisa from the Magalang or Sta. Rita producers</li>
    <li>San Nicolas pastries, the molded cookies named after the patron saint</li>
    <li>Sukang Sasa, the Pampanga palm vinegar</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May are the most comfortable. The Giant Lantern Festival peaks in mid-December and the city gets crowded that weekend. The Hot Air Balloon Festival is usually held in February at the Clark area, so plan around it if you want the sky show.</p>
<p>Pampanga rewards a slow itinerary. Two days, three different kinds of food, and a few quiet churches in between.</p>
