        'meta_title' => 'Pampanga Two-Day First-Timer Itinerary | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm two-day Pampanga plan covering San Fernando, Angeles, Candaba bird sanctuary, Bacolor church, and the Kapampangan food worth booking ahead.',
        'tags' => 'Pampanga, San Fernando, Angeles, Clark, Kapampangan',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'pampanga-province',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 7. Tarlac local guide
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2016/10/travel-guide-tarlac-tourist-spots-things-to-do.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Tarlac for First-Timers: The Province Manila Travelers Drive Past',
        'slug' => 'tarlac-first-timers-province-manila-drive-past',
        'excerpt' => 'Most travelers see Tarlac as a TPLEX exit on the way north. The province actually rewards a slow day. Here is the calm first-timer plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Tarlac is the province most Manila travelers blow past on the way to Baguio or Vigan. The TPLEX exits read like signposts, not destinations. But the province has Monasterio de Tarlac on a hill, the Aquino-Cojuangco Hacienda with its centuries-old church, the Capas National Shrine that marks the end of the Bataan Death March, and the gateway to Mt. Pinatubo. A slow day or an overnight is enough to see the highlights.</p>
<p>This is the calm read for first-time visitors who want to stop instead of pass through.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to SCTEX to TPLEX. The Tarlac City exit puts you at the provincial capital in around 90 minutes. The Capas exit is closer if you are starting at the Death March shrine or going to Pinatubo. Without a car, <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> and Genesis Bus both have direct routes from Cubao to Tarlac City.</p>
<h2>The Slow Day Plan</h2>
<p>Five stops is the realistic count for a single day. Pick three or four and accept that the rest will wait for the next visit.</p>
<h3>Monasterio de Tarlac</h3>
<p>The monastery sits on Mt. Resurrection in San Jose, on a ridge with a 30-foot statue of the Risen Christ. The chapel houses a relic believed to be a piece of the True Cross. The drive up is steep but paved, and the view from the top stretches across Central Luzon on a clear day. Wear modest clothing if you plan to enter the chapel.</p>
<h3>Capas National Shrine</h3>
<p>The shrine in Camp O'Donnell marks the end of the 1942 Bataan Death March. The 70-meter obelisk and the wall of names commemorate the Filipino and American soldiers who died in the camp. The site is open daylight hours and the visitor center has a short historical exhibit. The entrance fee is small. Bring water, there is little shade.</p>
<h3>Aquino-Cojuangco Hacienda and Sta. Ignacia Church</h3>
<p>The Aquino-Cojuangco Hacienda in Concepcion is the ancestral property of the family. The grounds include the old sugar mill and the Don Benigno Aquino Sr. monument. Sta. Ignacia Church, built in the 1700s, is one of the older Spanish-era churches in the region.</p>
<h3>Isdaan Floating Restaurant</h3>
<p>Isdaan in Gerona is a roadside themed restaurant with giant figures, fish ponds, and the famous Tacsiyapo Wall where you can throw clay pots at the wall to release stress. It is touristy in the best way, and the bangus and tilapia from the ponds are fresh.</p>
<h3>Aksu Mountain Resort and ANZAP Twin Falls</h3>
<p>For an outdoor stop, ANZAP Twin Falls in San Jose has a short hike to twin cascades. Aksu Mountain Resort in Mayantoc is the calmer base with cabins along the Nambalan River for those who want to overnight outside the city.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Iniruban, a Tarlac sticky-rice dessert wrapped in banana leaf</li>
    <li>Tupig from the roadside vendors in Concepcion</li>
    <li>Bopis Tarlac style, a heartier version than the Luzon norm</li>
    <li>Buko pie from the stalls along the highway</li>
    <li>Empanada at Tarlac State University area, the local meriendaplace</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where to Sleep</h2>
<p>Tarlac City has a handful of business-style hotels that work for a single night. For comparison, see <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g849915-Tarlac_City_Tarlac_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Capas has fewer choices but is closer to the Pinatubo trailhead if you are combining the two trips.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May are the most comfortable. The Belenismo sa Tarlac, a province-wide nativity scene contest, happens from November through January and is worth chasing across the towns if you visit in that window. December is festive, so book ahead.</p>
<p>Tarlac is not the destination most travelers chase, which is exactly why it stays calm. One day, three or four stops, and a quieter side of Central Luzon.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Tarlac First-Timer Guide: Beyond the TPLEX Exit | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm one-day Tarlac plan covering Monasterio de Tarlac, Capas National Shrine, Aquino-Cojuangco Hacienda, and Isdaan with practical bus and food notes.',
        'tags' => 'Tarlac, Monasterio, Capas Shrine, Central Luzon, day trip',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'tarlac',
    ],

