    // 8. Subic & Zambales things to do
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2021/03/things-to-do-in-subic-zambales-tourist-spots-itinerary.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Subic and Zambales in Two Days: Beyond the Theme Parks',
        'slug' => 'subic-zambales-two-days-beyond-theme-parks',
        'excerpt' => 'Subic gets the families and the theme park headlines. Zambales gets the coves. Here is the two-day plan that combines both without rushing.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Subic Bay Freeport and Zambales province sit on the same coast but get visited for different reasons. Subic draws the family weekenders for Zoobic, Ocean Adventure, and the duty-free shops. Zambales draws the campers for the Pundaquit coves and the surfers for Liwliwa. With two days you can do one side per day and still leave at a calm pace.</p>
<p>This is the calm first-timer read for a Subic-Zambales weekend.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Subic Freeport</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to SCTEX and exit at the Subic Bay Freeport. The drive is around two and a half hours in light traffic. The Freeport has its own road network, separate from the Olongapo grid outside.</p>
<h3>Morning: Zoobic Safari</h3>
<p>Zoobic Safari is the standard family pick. The tiger safari is the headline, a small bus drives through a fenced enclosure where tigers approach for chunks of raw meat. The savannah walk, croc park, and serpentarium round out the loop. Plan two to three hours.</p>
<h3>Afternoon: Ocean Adventure or JEST Camp</h3>
<p>Ocean Adventure in Camayan is the marine park with a small sea-lion and dolphin show. JEST Camp is the calmer alternative, an Aeta-led jungle environment survival camp that teaches fire-starting and basic foraging in a short guided walk. Pick one depending on your group.</p>
<h3>Evening: Harbor Point or Pier One</h3>
<p>Harbor Point is the air-conditioned mall for an easy dinner. Pier One along the waterfront has open-air dining with a view of the bay at sunset. Olongapo proper, just outside the Freeport gate, has the older bars and a few Korean and Vietnamese places worth trying.</p>
<h3>Night: Where to Sleep</h3>
<p>Stay inside the Freeport for the safer parking and easy access to day two attractions. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729261-Subic_Bay_Freeport_Zone_Olongapo_Zambales_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Zambales Coast</h2>
<p>From Subic, drive north along the coastal road through Castillejos, San Marcelino, and San Antonio. The drive to Pundaquit is around 90 minutes.</p>
<h3>Pundaquit and the Coves</h3>
<p>Pundaquit is the jump-off for Anawangin, Nagsasa, and Capones Island. For a day trip, the boatmen offer a three-island combo that visits Anawangin for a swim, Capones for the lighthouse, and Camara for the snorkeling. Pack a beach lunch from town because the islands have only minimal food stalls.</p>
<h3>Liwliwa for Surf and Sunset</h3>
<p>From San Antonio, continue 15 minutes north to Liwliwa in San Felipe. The beach is a long gray sand stretch with consistent surf in the habagat months from June to October. The Circle Hostel and a few small surf camps run lessons. The afternoon is the calmest for first-time surfers. Sunset is the closing photo.</p>
<h3>Optional: The Way Home via Iba</h3>
<p>If you have more time, drive 45 minutes further north to Iba for the provincial capital, then loop back via the Pinatubo Crater road to Capas if you want to add a Tarlac stop. Otherwise, return to Subic for dinner and head back to Manila on SCTEX.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Subic: fresh tuna and grilled liempo at Pier One</li>
    <li>Olongapo: sisig at Sit-N-Bull, an institution</li>
    <li>Iba: tilapia from the inland fishponds, served at roadside grills</li>
    <li>San Antonio: pakulot, the local steamed sweet snack</li>
    <li>Liwliwa: the surf camp kitchens for simple sinigang and rice bowls</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a hat for the cove day</li>
    <li>Aqua shoes for the rocky beach landings on Capones and Camara</li>
    <li>A dry bag for the boat ride</li>
    <li>Cash, the small towns past Subic have fewer ATMs</li>
    <li>A light jacket for the air-conditioned malls and the night drive back</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The Subic Freeport side works year round. The Zambales cove side runs best from November to May, with calmer water and clearer visibility. Surf at Liwliwa picks up from June to October. Avoid the typhoon weeks for either.</p>
<p>One Freeport day, one coast day, one quiet drive home. The Subic-Zambales weekend covers both sides of the same bay without rushing.</p>
