    // 9. Kaybiang Tunnel road trip
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2021/03/kaybiang-tunnel-road-trip-how-to-get-there-cavite.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Kaybiang Tunnel Road Trip: Ternate to Nasugbu in One Day',
        'slug' => 'kaybiang-tunnel-ternate-nasugbu-road-trip-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Kaybiang Tunnel cuts under Mt. Pico de Loro and connects Ternate to Nasugbu in one of the prettier coastal drives near Manila. Here is the day-trip plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Kaybiang Tunnel cuts under the Pico de Loro ridge and connects the Cavite town of Ternate to the Batangas town of Nasugbu. At around 300 meters long, it is one of the longest road tunnels in the country and the centerpiece of one of the more scenic coastal drives a short distance south of Manila. The tunnel itself takes 30 seconds to drive through, but the loop around it makes for a calm day-trip plan.</p>
<p>This is the practical read for first-time drivers.</p>
<h2>The Route</h2>
<p>From Manila, take CAVITEX or SLEX-CALAX to the Tagaytay-Nasugbu road, then descend through Nasugbu to the coastal highway. Alternatively, you can go via Cavite, through Imus, Naic, and Maragondon, exiting at the Ternate coastal road. Both routes take around three hours including stops, and you can drive in one direction and return the other to make it a real loop.</p>
<h3>Driving Direction</h3>
<p>Most drivers prefer the Ternate-to-Nasugbu direction in the morning, because the sun is at your back through the tunnel and the coastline opens dramatically when you exit the south side. The Nasugbu-to-Ternate direction in the afternoon gives you the western sun for sunset shots from the lookout point above Hamilo Coast.</p>
<h2>The Stops Along the Way</h2>
<p>The drive itself is the attraction, but the stops are what make the day.</p>
<h3>Puerto Azul Junction</h3>
<p>Before the tunnel from the Ternate side, the road passes the entrance to the old Puerto Azul resort area. The lookouts here give the first wide view of the Manila Bay coast. Pull off for a coffee at the small roadside stalls.</p>
<h3>Kaybiang Tunnel Itself</h3>
<p>The tunnel was built in 2009 and opened to traffic in 2013. The walls are lined with reflective tiles and the lighting is good. Slow down on entry because the temperature drops noticeably inside. Do not stop inside the tunnel, the road shoulders are too narrow.</p>
<h3>Pico de Loro Cove Lookout</h3>
<p>South of the tunnel, the road climbs to a lookout above Hamilo Coast and the Pico de Loro Cove. The pull-off is on the seaward side and the view stretches across the bay to the Pico de Loro silhouette inland. This is the standard photo stop for the route.</p>
<h3>Nasugbu Town</h3>
<p>The Nasugbu town proper is around 20 minutes further south. The main beach is public and the Wawa side has the food stalls. The Sanctuario de San Antonio church is the heritage stop if you want to slow down.</p>
<h2>Side Trips</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Pico de Loro mountain trail at Mt. Palay-Palay National Park, half-day hike from the DENR trailhead at the Ternate side</li>
    <li>Caleruega Church in the Tagaytay-Nasugbu road, a calm retreat stop</li>
    <li>Fortune Island in Nasugbu, the day-trip island with the white pillars</li>
    <li>Tagaytay Ridge for dinner at a Mahogany Market grill on the way home</li>
</ul>
<h2>Driving Notes</h2>
<p>The roads are paved but narrow in stretches, especially near the tunnel. Watch for tricycles and the occasional carabao cart. The descent from the Tagaytay-Nasugbu ridge has sharp curves, drive in low gear if you are in a smaller car. Fuel up in Ternate or Nasugbu town because the stretches between have limited stations.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May give the clearest views. The tunnel can flood at the lower section during heavy rains in July and August, which sometimes closes the road for a few hours. Weekends bring more traffic, especially Sunday afternoons. Weekday is the calmest.</p>
<h2>Where to Stop for Lunch</h2>
<p>The cleanest lunch options are in Nasugbu town proper for fresh seafood, or up at Tagaytay for the bulalo and tawilis if you are looping back via the ridge. For an overnight, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g664650-Nasugbu_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>One tunnel, two provinces, one slow coastal loop. The Kaybiang drive rewards the early start.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Kaybiang Tunnel Road Trip: Ternate to Nasugbu | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm one-day road trip through Kaybiang Tunnel connecting Ternate to Nasugbu. The route, the lookouts, the side trips, and when to drive.',
        'tags' => 'Kaybiang Tunnel, Ternate, Nasugbu, road trip, Cavite Batangas',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'nasugbu',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 10. Boracay de Cavite Ternate (use naic key)
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2014/04/boracay-de-cavite-marine-base-ternate-cavite.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Boracay de Cavite: The Quiet Beach Inside the Marine Base',
        'slug' => 'boracay-de-cavite-katungkulan-ternate-marine-base',
        'excerpt' => 'Boracay de Cavite is a quiet beach inside the Marine Base at Ternate. Here is how to enter, what to expect, and why it works as a calm day trip.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Boracay de Cavite is the local name for Katungkulan Beach, a stretch of fine pale-gray sand on the western side of the Ternate peninsula. The beach sits inside the Philippine Marine Base, which means access is by registration and the area stays quiet compared to the open coastal stops further south. The nickname is generous, the water and sand are clearly not Boracay, but the calm and the lack of crowds make it a sensible day trip from Manila.</p>
<p>This is the practical read for first-timers.</p>
<h2>Getting In</h2>
<p>The base sits at the western tip of Ternate, past Puerto Azul. From Manila, the drive is around two and a half to three hours via CAVITEX, the Coastal Road, and Tanza, then through Naic and Maragondon into Ternate. Without a car, take a Saulog or Erjohn bus from Pasay or Lawton to Ternate town, then a tricycle to the Marine Base gate.</p>
<h3>The Entry Process</h3>
<p>At the gate, you register names and present a valid government ID. The guard issues a day pass and explains the rules. The entrance fee is small, and there are no advance reservations needed for day visitors. The pass is good for daylight hours only, with everyone out by sunset.</p>
<h2>What the Beach Looks Like</h2>
<p>Katungkulan is around 700 meters long, ending in a small rocky outcrop at the south end. The sand is pale gray, almost cream in the late afternoon light, and the water is shallow for a long stretch before it drops off. The bay is sheltered, so the water stays calm even when the open coast outside is choppy. Behind the beach are pine trees and a small grass field, with concrete picnic tables under the shade.</p>
<h3>What There Is and Is Not</h3>
<p>There are basic shower stalls, restrooms, and a few small stores selling cold drinks and instant noodles. There is no restaurant. There is no resort. There is no overnight accommodation for civilians. There is also no Wi-Fi and the signal is patchy. This is intentional, the base preserves the spot as a quiet recreation area for personnel and visitors.</p>
<h2>The Day Plan</h2>
<p>Arrive by 8 a.m. to have the beach mostly to yourself for the morning. The midday sun is strong, so plan to swim early, eat lunch in the shade, and use the afternoon for a slower walk to the rocky end. Snorkeling along the south rocks gives glimpses of small reef fish if the water is clear.</p>
<h3>What to Bring</h3>
<ul>
    <li>A valid government ID for each adult in the group</li>
    <li>Beach mat or picnic blanket, the tables fill quickly on weekends</li>
    <li>Packed lunch and water, there is no food vendor inside</li>
    <li>Trash bags, the base requires you to pack everything out</li>
    <li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a wide hat</li>
    <li>Slippers and aqua shoes for the rocky south end</li>
    <li>A power bank, the outlets near the showers are limited</li>
    <li>Cash for the entrance fee and the small store</li>
</ul>
<h2>Side Trips on the Way Back</h2>
<p>The drive home pairs naturally with one or two extra stops in Ternate and the surrounding towns.</p>
<ul>
    <li>Kaybiang Tunnel, around 20 minutes south, the long road tunnel through Mt. Pico de Loro</li>
    <li>Caracol of Ternate, a small chapel built on a hill above the bay</li>
    <li>Maragondon historical area, where the Bonifacio brothers were tried in 1897</li>
    <li>Naic public market for fresh seafood pasalubong on the way back</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May are the best, with the calmest water and the clearest sky. Avoid the typhoon weeks from August to October because the access roads can be temporarily blocked by landslides between Maragondon and Ternate. Weekdays are noticeably quieter than weekends. The base closes occasionally for official events, so check ahead by calling the Ternate municipal office.</p>
<h2>If You Want to Overnight</h2>
<p>There is no in-base overnight option for civilians. The nearest accommodations are in Nasugbu, Batangas, around 40 minutes south through the Kaybiang Tunnel. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g664650-Nasugbu_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Boracay de Cavite is not the Boracay it borrows the name from. It is a quiet beach inside a Marine Base, which is why it stays quiet, which is why it is worth the drive.</p>
