    // 11. Cavite 30 tourist spots → silang
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2021/03/things-to-do-in-cavite-tourist-spots-itinerary.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Cavite First-Timer Loop: From Silang Cafes to Corregidor',
        'slug' => 'cavite-first-timer-loop-silang-cafes-corregidor',
        'excerpt' => 'Cavite is the province where Philippine independence was declared. Here is the first-timer loop that hits the cafes, the history, and the coast in two days.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cavite is the province most Manila travelers know for one of three things, the cafes of Silang and Tagaytay, the heritage trail in Kawit and Imus, or the long beach drives along the western coast. The province is bigger than its reputation, and a two-day loop can hit all three sides without backtracking. This is the calm first-timer read.</p>
<p>The full loop starts at the Silang upland, descends through Tagaytay border, sweeps west via Naic to Ternate, then heads back north through Maragondon, Kawit, and Imus on the way home.</p>
<h2>Day 1: The Uplands</h2>
<p>From Manila, take CAVITEX or SLEX-CALAX to Silang. The drive is around 90 minutes in light traffic. Silang sits at around 400 meters elevation, cooler than the lowland coast.</p>
<h3>Silang Cafes</h3>
<p>The Aguinaldo Highway from Silang to Tagaytay is the cafe corridor. Bag of Beans, Cafe Voi La, Marcia Adams, and a dozen smaller new openings line the road. Pick two and skip the rest, otherwise you end up stuck on the road too long. The breakfast plates at Marcia Adams are the most popular.</p>
<h3>Tagaytay Ridge for Lunch</h3>
<p>Stop for bulalo and tawilis at the Mahogany Market or Diner's. The Taal Volcano view from the ridge is the standard photo. Skylight Garden and the People's Park in the Sky are calmer stops outside the main strip.</p>
<h3>Tropical Plant Visit at Antipolo Garden Center or Costales Farm</h3>
<p>If you skipped Tagaytay for plants, Costales Nature Farm in Majayjay extends into Cavite. Costales offers a quiet half-day for organic farming tours.</p>
<h3>Night: Where to Sleep</h3>
<p>Tagaytay has the widest range of accommodations within easy reach of Cavite. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g303330-Tagaytay_Cavite_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Silang has fewer but quieter inns.</p>
<h2>Day 2: The Coast and the Heritage Trail</h2>
<p>Leave Silang or Tagaytay by 7 a.m. and descend west to Nasugbu, then back into Cavite via the Kaybiang Tunnel into Ternate.</p>
<h3>Kaybiang Tunnel and Ternate</h3>
<p>The 300-meter road tunnel under Mt. Pico de Loro connects Nasugbu to Ternate. From there, you can swing by Boracay de Cavite in the Marine Base for a short beach stop, or continue north through Maragondon to begin the heritage leg.</p>
<h3>Maragondon Historical Trail</h3>
<p>Maragondon is where the Bonifacio brothers were tried and condemned in 1897. The Bonifacio trial house is preserved as a museum. The town church next door dates to the 1700s and has an old organ.</p>
<h3>Kawit Aguinaldo Shrine</h3>
<p>The Aguinaldo Shrine in Kawit is where Philippine independence was declared in 1898. The mansion and the museum tour take around an hour. The flag-raising room is the standard photo stop.</p>
<h3>Imus Cathedral and the Plaza</h3>
<p>The Imus Cathedral and the surrounding plaza are the last stop before returning to Manila. The Battle of Imus marker and the heritage houses around the plaza give the colonial-era street feel.</p>
<h2>Corregidor as a Separate Trip</h2>
<p>Corregidor Island sits at the entrance of Manila Bay, technically part of Cavite. The standard day tour leaves from CCP Bay Terminal in Manila on a Sun Cruises ferry, not from any Cavite port. It is the World War II battle site with the Malinta Tunnel, the Battery Way, and the Pacific War Memorial. Plan it as a separate full day, not part of the road loop.</p>
<h2>What to Eat</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Silang and Tagaytay: cafe breakfasts, bulalo, tawilis</li>
    <li>Indang: empanada Caviteno style with chorizo</li>
    <li>Naic and Ternate: fresh tuna and grilled liempo</li>
    <li>Kawit and Imus: longganisa Imus, the garlicky pork sausage</li>
    <li>Bacoor: fresh oysters and tahong from the bay</li>
</ul>
<h2>Driving Notes</h2>
<p>CAVITEX is the fastest way in and out for the coastal towns. The Aguinaldo Highway is the spine of the upland leg. Watch for the tricycles and the slow turns through Maragondon. Most stations are along the highway, fuel up before turning to the smaller barrios.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May are the most comfortable for the coastal leg. The uplands stay cool year round. Avoid the Holy Week weekend, when Tagaytay traffic jams from the morning onward.</p>
<p>Two days, three different sides of Cavite. The province rewards a slow loop more than a single-spot day trip.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Cavite First-Timer Loop: Silang to Corregidor | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm two-day Cavite loop covering Silang cafes, Tagaytay ridge, Kaybiang Tunnel, Maragondon, Kawit, and Imus heritage stops.',
        'tags' => 'Cavite, Silang, Tagaytay, Kawit, Imus, heritage',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'silang',
    ],

