    // 13. Calaguas Camarines Norte
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2014/04/beaches-near-manila-for-less-than-1000.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Calaguas Islands: The Long Bus and Bangka Trip Worth Taking',
        'slug' => 'calaguas-islands-camarines-norte-long-bus-bangka-trip',
        'excerpt' => 'Calaguas Islands in Camarines Norte have the powder-white sand of Boracay without the crowds. Here is the long bus and bangka route worth taking once.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Calaguas Islands sit off the northern tip of Camarines Norte, around eight hours of travel from Manila by bus and bangka combined. The main island, Tinaga, has a beach called Mahabang Buhangin that earned the comparison to Boracay before Boracay became Boracay. The sand is fine and white, the water is clear, and the camping setup is intentionally minimal. There are no big resorts. There is no electricity beyond solar panels. There is no Wi-Fi. This is the calm read for first-timers.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>The trip is the trade-off for the quiet. From Manila, take a <a href="https://www.dltbco.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">DLTB Co.</a> or Superlines bus from Pasay or Cubao bound for Daet, Camarines Norte. The ride is around eight to nine hours. From Daet, take a jeepney or van to Vinzons or Paracale, where the bangka pier is. From the pier, the bangka to Calaguas takes around two hours depending on sea conditions.</p>
<h3>The Bangka Schedule</h3>
<p>The morning bangka leaves Vinzons or Paracale at around 10 a.m. and returns from Calaguas at around 11 a.m. the next day. There is usually one trip per day each way. Most travelers join a tour package that includes the bangka, the camping fee, and meals, which is easier than DIY because the boatmen are not always at the pier for individual bookings.</p>
<h2>What Mahabang Buhangin Looks Like</h2>
<p>The main beach is a 1.5-kilometer curve of fine white sand. The water is clear and shallow for a long stretch before it drops off. The hills behind the beach are green and grassy, with a small cross at the top of the highest hill that you can hike to in around 30 minutes. The view from the cross is the standard Calaguas photo.</p>
<h3>The Camping Setup</h3>
<p>The accommodations are tents pitched on platforms or under simple bamboo shelters. A few cottages exist for those who want more comfort. The bathrooms are basic with hand-pump showers. The kitchen is communal, run by the boat operator or the camp staff, with meals included in most packages.</p>
<h2>The Two-Night Plan</h2>
<p>Two nights is the right length. One night is rushed because the bangka schedule eats half a day on each side. Three nights starts to feel long unless you really want to disconnect.</p>
<h3>Day 1: Arrive and Walk</h3>
<p>Arrive by lunch, set up the tent, eat the camp meal, and walk the full length of the beach in the afternoon. Swim before sunset, then watch the stars after dinner. The lack of light pollution makes the Milky Way visible on clear nights from January to April.</p>
<h3>Day 2: Hike and Snorkel</h3>
<p>Wake early for the hike up to the cross. The trail is steep and takes around 30 minutes one way. Back at the beach, breakfast, then a snorkel tour to the nearby Maculabo or Pinagtigasan Islands. The bangka takes you for half a day, with stops at small coves and reefs.</p>
<h3>Day 3: Slow Morning and Departure</h3>
<p>Pack up by 10 a.m. for the 11 a.m. bangka back. The return trip is calmer in the morning before the wind picks up. From Vinzons or Paracale, take the van back to Daet, then the night bus to Manila.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Tent and sleeping mat if you DIY, otherwise the camp provides</li>
    <li>Headlamp or flashlight, the camp uses minimal lighting</li>
    <li>At least three liters of drinking water per person per day</li>
    <li>Snacks and instant coffee, the camp meals are basic</li>
    <li>Trash bag, pack out everything you bring in</li>
    <li>Reef-safe sunscreen, a hat, and a rashguard</li>
    <li>Insect repellent for dusk</li>
    <li>A power bank or two, no charging outlets</li>
    <li>Cash, no ATMs anywhere near the bangka piers</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from March to May are the best, with the calmest sea and the clearest sky. The window from October to February has cooler weather but rougher water that sometimes cancels the bangka trips. Avoid the typhoon weeks from July to October because the Pacific side of Luzon catches the worst of the storms.</p>
<h2>Where to Sleep in Daet</h2>
<p>If you need a hotel before or after the trip, Daet town has basic options. You can compare on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g4109075-Daet_Camarines_Norte_Province_Bicol_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Calaguas is not a quick weekend. It is a slow long-weekend trip that earns the long bus ride. Once is enough for most travelers, and that once stays in the memory.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Calaguas Islands Camping Trip from Manila | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm DIY guide to Calaguas Islands in Camarines Norte. The bus route via Daet, the bangka schedule, the two-night camping plan, and what to bring.',
        'tags' => 'Calaguas, Camarines Norte, camping, Mahabang Buhangin, islands',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'naga-camarines-sur',
    ],

