    // 14. Mt. Gulugod Baboy
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2011/10/climbing-tips-mt-gulugod-baboy.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Gulugod Baboy: The Easy Mabini Day Hike for First-Time Climbers',
        'slug' => 'mt-gulugod-baboy-mabini-easy-day-hike-first-time',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Gulugod Baboy in Mabini, Batangas is one of the friendliest first hikes near Manila. Here is the trail, the view of Anilao, and the side trip to Sombrero.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Gulugod Baboy in Mabini, Batangas is one of the easier introductions to Philippine day hiking. The mountain sits at 525 meters above sea level, the trail is open grassland with light tree cover, and the climb to the summit takes around two hours at a calm pace. The summit ridge gives a panoramic view of the Anilao bay, Verde Island, and the silhouette of Mindoro across the channel. It is the rare hike where the view earns the effort without punishing your legs.</p>
<p>This is the calm first-timer read for a Gulugod Baboy day plan.</p>
<h2>Getting to the Trailhead</h2>
<p>The standard jump-off is the Philpan Dive Resort in Brgy. Anilao Proper, Mabini. From Manila, take a <a href="https://www.dltbco.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">DLTB Co.</a> or Jam Liner bus from Cubao or Buendia bound for Batangas Pier. Get off at Batangas Grand Terminal, then take a jeepney to Mabini and a tricycle to Anilao Proper. The trip from Manila takes around three to four hours total.</p>
<h3>Driving Option</h3>
<p>If you drive, the route is SLEX to STAR Tollway, exit at Batangas City, then take the Mabini road. The drive is around two and a half hours from Manila in light traffic.</p>
<h2>The Trail</h2>
<p>From the Philpan Dive Resort gate, the trail starts as a concrete road that gradually shifts to a dirt path through cogon grass and bamboo groves. The first section climbs steadily through the village outskirts. The second section opens into rolling grass hills with no shade. The summit ridge is reached after the third section, a final 20-minute climb to the highest point.</p>
<h3>Pace and Time</h3>
<p>A calm climber takes around two hours to reach the summit, with several rest stops along the way. A faster pace gets you there in 90 minutes. Bring water, the trail has no springs and the village water is for residents.</p>
<h3>Trail Markings</h3>
<p>The path is well worn and easy to follow on clear days. On overcast days the upper grass section can be confusing because the trail branches into cow paths. Stick to the path with the most foot traffic, or hire a local guide from the trailhead for a small fee.</p>
<h2>The Summit View</h2>
<p>The ridge gives the wide view in three directions. East faces Verde Island and the Maricaban Strait, the standard photo. North faces the Anilao bay, where the dive boats anchor. South faces the Sombrero Island and the Mindoro silhouette on a clear day. The summit itself has no marker beyond a few cairns and an old metal pole.</p>
<h3>Sit for Lunch</h3>
<p>Pack a sandwich and eat it at the ridge. The breeze keeps the heat manageable, and the grass makes a soft seat. Bring a small trash bag and pack out everything.</p>
<h2>The Sombrero Side Trip</h2>
<p>After the hike, the standard plan is to descend, eat a late lunch at the trailhead, then take a bangka from the Philpan beach to Sombrero Island for an afternoon snorkel. The crossing takes around 20 minutes. Sombrero is a small uninhabited island with a sandy point and a reef on the lee side. The bangka rate is fixed by the local tourism office.</p>
<h3>What Sombrero Offers</h3>
<ul>
    <li>A clear shallow reef with small tropical fish</li>
    <li>A short walk to the higher point of the island for a view</li>
    <li>A sandy strip for a swim before the ride back</li>
    <li>Cold buko from the bangka operator if you order ahead</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Closed shoes or trail runners with grip</li>
    <li>At least two liters of water per person</li>
    <li>Reef-safe sunscreen, a wide hat, and a rashguard</li>
    <li>A packed lunch and trash bag</li>
    <li>A light dry bag for the Sombrero crossing</li>
    <li>Insect repellent for the lower trail</li>
    <li>Cash for the trail fee, the bangka, and the trailhead drinks</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May are the safest. The trail can be muddy and slippery during the rains from June to October. Start the hike by 6 a.m. to summit before 9 a.m. and beat the midday heat. The sun on the grass ridge is brutal by 11 a.m.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>If you want an overnight in Anilao, the dive resorts cluster along the same Anilao Proper coast. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g6829447-Anilao_Mabini_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Pair the hike with a discovery dive or a snorkel the next day if you have time.</p>
<p>Gulugod Baboy is the calm first hike. Climb in the morning, eat lunch at the trailhead, then take the bangka to Sombrero. One day, two reads of Mabini.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Gulugod Baboy Day Hike from Manila | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm first-timer guide to Mt. Gulugod Baboy in Mabini. The trail, the Anilao bay view, the Sombrero Island side trip, and what to pack.',
        'tags' => 'Mt Gulugod Baboy, Mabini, Anilao, day hike, Batangas',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'anilao-mabini',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 15. Mt. Manunggal Cebu
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2013/03/relieving-history-by-climbing-mt-manunggal.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Manunggal Cebu: The Magsaysay Memorial Day Hike',
        'slug' => 'mt-manunggal-cebu-magsaysay-memorial-day-hike',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Manunggal in Balamban, Cebu is where President Magsaysay crashed in 1957. Here is the hike that pairs the memorial with a calm ridge campsite.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Manunggal sits in Balamban, on the western side of Cebu Island, at around 1,100 meters above sea level. The mountain is best known as the site of the 1957 plane crash that killed President Ramon Magsaysay along with most of his staff. A simple memorial near the campsite marks the spot, with parts of the aircraft preserved in place. The hike to the summit is a calm day climb that also works as an overnight if you want to camp at the meadow near the memorial. This is the practical read.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>From Cebu City, take a Ceres bus or a van bound for Tabuelan from the Cebu North Bus Terminal. Ask the driver to drop you at the Magsaysay Park junction in Brgy. Magsaysay, Balamban. The ride takes around two hours. From the junction, hire a habal-habal motorcycle to the trailhead at the cement marker. The habal-habal ride is around 20 minutes on a rough mountain road.</p>
<h3>Driving Option</h3>
<p>If you drive, take the Transcentral Highway from Cebu City over the central ridge, then turn off at the Balamban side toward Magsaysay. The drive is around two hours one way. Park at the trailhead if there is space, or arrange to leave the car at the barangay hall for a small fee.</p>
<h2>The Trail</h2>
<p>The standard trail from the cement marker to the summit takes around two to three hours at a calm pace. The path crosses cogon grass, scrub forest, and a few short clearings. There is light tree cover in the middle stretch but the upper section opens into the meadow that hosts the Magsaysay memorial and the official campsite.</p>
<h3>The Memorial</h3>
<p>The crash site is in the meadow near the campsite, marked by a small concrete monument and parts of the C-47 aircraft, including the wing and a piece of the fuselage. The Bureau of Soils and Water Management built a marker on the spot. The memorial is quiet, surrounded by trees, and most visitors spend some time reading the engraved text before continuing to the summit.</p>
<h3>The Summit</h3>
<p>From the memorial, a short final climb of around 20 minutes leads to the summit. The view stretches across Balamban toward the Camotes Sea on a clear day, and on the other side to the Tanon Strait between Cebu and Negros. The summit itself has no marker beyond a few small cairns.</p>
<h2>The Overnight Plan</h2>
<p>The meadow near the memorial is the standard campsite. Around a dozen tents fit comfortably. There is a small spring nearby for water, but treat or boil it before drinking. The cleared area has space for a small fire pit, but bring your own wood because the area is protected and gathering firewood is not allowed.</p>
<h3>Why Overnight Works</h3>
<p>The summit views are best at sunrise, when the morning light cuts through the mist that often forms in the valleys overnight. Climbing in the late afternoon, camping at the memorial, and waking before dawn for the summit push gives the most rewarding window. The temperature at the camp can drop to around 15 degrees Celsius on cooler nights, so bring a fleece and a sleeping bag.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Tent and sleeping mat if overnighting</li>
    <li>A fleece or warm layer for the night</li>
    <li>At least three liters of water per person per day</li>
    <li>Headlamp and extra batteries</li>
    <li>Trash bag, pack everything out</li>
    <li>Closed trekking shoes with grip</li>
    <li>A light raincoat, the upper meadow catches passing showers</li>
    <li>Cash for the habal-habal, the barangay fee, and the guide</li>
</ul>
<h2>Guide and Fee</h2>
<p>The barangay requires a guide for first-time climbers. The local tourism office at the Magsaysay junction can arrange one for a small fee. The guide knows the trail branches and can also explain the local stories around the Magsaysay crash. There is also an environmental fee collected at the trailhead.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from December to May are the safest. The wet season from June to November can make the trail muddy and the views obscured by mist. Weekends are the busiest, mostly with student climbers from Cebu. Weekday climbs are quieter. Avoid climbing during typhoon weeks.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay in Cebu</h2>
<p>For places to sleep in Cebu City before or after the hike, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298460-Cebu_City_Cebu_Island_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Most climbers stay in the city for the easy bus access on hike morning.</p>
<p>Manunggal pairs a quiet history lesson with a manageable summit. The crash site is sobering. The view is generous. The overnight is worth the small effort.</p>
