    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 16. Gigantes Islands Iloilo
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2015/11/top-things-to-do-in-gigantes-islands-iloilo-travel-guide.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Gigantes Islands Hopping: Carles, Iloilo in Three Days',
        'slug' => 'gigantes-islands-carles-iloilo-three-day-island-hopping',
        'excerpt' => 'Gigantes Islands in Carles, northern Iloilo are the calmer alternative to the busier island groups. Here is the three-day DIY plan from Iloilo City.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Gigantes Islands sit at the northern tip of Iloilo, a cluster of around ten small limestone islands divided into Gigantes Norte and Gigantes Sur. The names you will hear repeatedly are Cabugao Gamay for the famous postcard cove, Tangke for the saltwater lagoon, Bantigue for the long sandbar, Antonia for the swim beach, and Pawikan Cave for the limestone interior. The scallop trade is the local livelihood, and the seafood is part of the trip.</p>
<p>This is the practical three-day read from Iloilo City.</p>
<h2>Getting There</h2>
<p>Fly into <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Iloilo Airport</a> on Cebu Pacific or Philippine Airlines. From the airport, take a shuttle to the city, then transfer to the Tagbak Terminal for a Ceres bus bound for Estancia or Bancal Port. The bus ride is around four to five hours. From Bancal Port, take a bangka to Gigantes Norte, around an hour to 90 minutes depending on sea conditions.</p>
<h3>Easier: Package Tour</h3>
<p>The DIY route is doable but the connections are tight. A package tour from Iloilo City handles the van transfer, the bangka, the island hopping fees, and the overnight accommodation. Most agencies in Iloilo City and on Boracay run weekend departures.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Travel and Settle</h2>
<p>The travel day eats most of the daylight. Plan to arrive at Gigantes Norte by mid-afternoon. Drop your bags at a small guesthouse in Brgy. Asluman, eat fresh scallops at the village kitchens, and walk the village beach at sunset. There is no nightlife. The early sleep prepares you for the next morning's island hopping.</p>
<h3>Where to Sleep</h3>
<p>Most accommodations on Gigantes Norte are small guesthouses and a few simple beachfront cottages. The bigger jump-off resort is Solina Beach in Estancia, which works if you want a comfortable base before the bangka transfer. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7165611-Carles_Iloilo_Province_Western_Visayas_Region_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>Day 2: The Full Island Hopping Loop</h2>
<p>The standard tour covers four to five stops over a full day. The bangka leaves the village pier at 8 a.m. and returns at 4 p.m. Pack lunch, sunscreen, and a dry bag.</p>
<h3>Cabugao Gamay</h3>
<p>The first stop is usually Cabugao Gamay, the small island with the famous viewpoint. Climb the short trail to the rocky outcrop above the cove for the postcard shot, then swim at the white sandbar that connects the two halves of the island. The water is shallow and clear.</p>
<h3>Tangke Lagoon</h3>
<p>Tangke is a saltwater lagoon inside Gigantes Sur, accessible by a narrow channel that opens only at certain tides. The bangka anchors outside and you swim in through the gap. The lagoon is surrounded by limestone cliffs and the water is calm. The swim out can be tricky if the tide is dropping, so listen to the boatman.</p>
<h3>Bantigue Sandbar</h3>
<p>Bantigue is the long sandbar that appears at low tide. The strip stretches for around a kilometer of fine white sand and crystal water. Lunch is usually served here, grilled fish and rice on a small island setup with banig mats and shade.</p>
<h3>Antonia Beach</h3>
<p>Antonia is the swim beach with a small entrance fee and basic facilities. Snorkel the rocky edges for small reef fish. The water is the deepest of the four stops, so non-swimmers should stay close to the shore.</p>
<h3>Pawikan Cave</h3>
<p>Pawikan Cave on Gigantes Norte is the limestone cave that local fishermen used to shelter during storms. The walk through requires a small flashlight, and the cave opens to a high chamber with stalactites. The visit is short, around 30 minutes, but the cave is worth the stop.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Scallop Lunch and Departure</h2>
<p>The bangka back to Bancal Port leaves around 11 a.m. Use the morning for a slow village walk, breakfast of fresh fish, and a scallop lunch before the boat. Carles is the scallop capital, and the village kitchens prepare them in butter, garlic, and cheese variations.</p>
<h3>Returning to Iloilo</h3>
<p>From Bancal Port, take the Ceres bus back to Iloilo City. The trip is around four to five hours. Plan a buffer night in Iloilo City if your flight is the next morning.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Reef-safe sunscreen, a hat, and a rashguard</li>
    <li>Aqua shoes for the limestone landings</li>
    <li>Dry bag for camera and phone</li>
    <li>Cash, no ATMs on Gigantes</li>
    <li>Power bank, brownouts are common</li>
    <li>Headlamp for evening and the Pawikan Cave</li>
    <li>Light raincoat for sudden showers</li>
    <li>Snorkel and mask if you have your own</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from March to May are the best, with the calmest sea and clearest water. The wet season from June to October has rougher water that can cancel the bangka trips. Avoid the typhoon weeks. Long weekends fill up fast, so book ahead.</p>
<p>Gigantes is the slower, quieter island-hopping trip Western Visayas travelers underrate. Three days is the right length, the scallops are part of the kwento, and the postcards do not lie.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Gigantes Islands Carles, Iloilo Three-Day Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm three-day DIY guide to Gigantes Islands in Carles, Iloilo. The bus and bangka route, the island hopping stops, the scallop lunches, and what to bring.',
        'tags' => 'Gigantes Islands, Carles, Iloilo, island hopping, scallops',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'iloilo-city',
