    // 17. Davao City local guide
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2016/08/davao-city-travel-guide-tourist-spots-and-attractions.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Davao City for First-Timers: A Local Reading of the Slow Two Days',
        'slug' => 'davao-city-first-timers-local-slow-two-days',
        'excerpt' => 'Davao City rewards first-timers who plan two days instead of one. Here is the calm local read covering Roxas Avenue food, Eden, Samal, and the durian etiquette.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Davao City is the largest city in Mindanao by land area and one of the easiest urban destinations in the country for first-time visitors. The city is clean, the smoking ban is enforced, the rules are quietly visible, and the local food scene runs from grilled tuna jaws at Roxas Avenue to durian shakes at Magsaysay Park. The trick is to plan two days instead of one, so you can pair the city sights with a half-day trip to Eden Nature Park or Samal Island without rushing either side.</p>
<p>This is the calm first-timer read.</p>
<h2>Getting In</h2>
<p>Fly into Francisco Bangoy International Airport in Davao on <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a>, Philippine Airlines, or AirAsia. The airport is around 30 minutes from the city center by Grab or taxi. The fixed-rate taxis from the airport queue are reliable. Grab works well in the city itself.</p>
<h2>Day 1: City and Roxas Avenue</h2>
<p>Stay in a hotel near Roxas Avenue or in the Lanang business area for easy access to the city sights and the food strip.</p>
<h3>Morning: People's Park and the Walking Loop</h3>
<p>People's Park in the city center is a calm three-hectare urban park with sculptures of the Lumad and indigenous peoples of Mindanao. From there, walk to the San Pedro Cathedral, the oldest church in the city, and the City Hall. The walk takes around an hour at a slow pace.</p>
<h3>Lunch: Marco Polo Café or a Local Carinderia</h3>
<p>For a sit-down lunch with a city view, the Marco Polo Davao on Claro M. Recto has a buffet on the upper floor. For a local carinderia experience, try Ahfat Seafood Plaza or any of the Boulevard restaurants for fresh seafood at lower prices.</p>
<h3>Afternoon: Museo Dabawenyo and D'Bone Collector Museum</h3>
<p>Museo Dabawenyo is a small free museum that tells the story of the city through the lens of the eleven tribes that originally lived in the area. D'Bone Collector Museum near Bucana is a curious private collection of animal skeletons that doubles as a marine conservation talk for kids.</p>
<h3>Night: Roxas Avenue Food Strip</h3>
<p>Roxas Avenue is the night food strip. The grilled tuna jaws are the local headline. The standard order is panga ng tuna with rice and a soda. The strip starts at the Bonifacio Street end and runs for around three blocks. Eat early to avoid the queue.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Eden Nature Park or Samal Island</h2>
<p>Pick one for day two.</p>
<h3>Option A: Eden Nature Park</h3>
<p>Eden Nature Park sits in the Toril district, around 45 minutes from the city center. The park is at around 900 meters elevation, so the air is cool and the temperature drops several degrees compared to the city. The standard day tour covers a shuttle ride through the garden, a buffet lunch, and an optional sky cycle or zipline. The Lola's Garden and Lawn for picnics are the calm spots. Bring a light jacket.</p>
<h3>Option B: Samal Island</h3>
<p>Samal Island is reached by a 10-minute ferry from the Sasa Wharf. From the Samal landing, hire a habal-habal or a van to one of the beach areas. The Hagimit Falls is the freshwater stop, the Pearl Farm side has the calmer beaches, and the Monfort Bat Cave hosts the largest known colony of fruit bats in the world. A half-day works for one or two stops, a full day for three.</p>
<h2>Durian Etiquette</h2>
<p>Davao is the durian capital. The strong smell that some hotels ban is part of the deal, so eat it at the public markets, the Magsaysay Park stalls, or the Aldevinco Shopping Center. The vendors will open and clean a fruit for you and let you eat on the spot. The standard pairing is mangosteen, which the locals say balances the heat.</p>
<h3>Pasalubong</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Dried mangoes and durian candies from Aldevinco</li>
    <li>Coffee beans from the Mt. Apo highlands</li>
    <li>Tablea, the local chocolate disks for sikwate</li>
    <li>T'nalak woven cloth from the T'boli community</li>
    <li>Frozen durian if your destination allows it on the plane</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Know</h2>
<ul>
    <li>The smoking ban is strictly enforced, smoke only in designated areas</li>
    <li>The speed limit on city roads is 30 kph, taxis respect this</li>
    <li>Tap water is potable in most areas but bottled is the safer first-timer choice</li>
    <li>Grab is widely available and reliable</li>
    <li>Cash is preferred at smaller carinderias and the durian stalls</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where to Sleep</h2>
<p>For a comfortable first-timer base, the Lanang area near SM Lanang has the larger hotels and easy access to the airport. For walking distance to the night food strip, choose around Roxas Avenue. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298460-Davao_City_Davao_del_Sur_Province_Davao_Region_Mindanao-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>Davao has a year-round mild climate, but the dry months from December to May are the most comfortable. The Kadayawan Festival in mid-August is the city's biggest annual event, with parades and indigenous dance presentations. Hotels fill up fast that week.</p>
<p>Davao rewards a slow two-day plan. The city, the durian, and one half-day side trip. The kwento writes itself.</p>
