    // 18. Quezon Province beaches
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2017/01/top-best-beautiful-beaches-in-quezon.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Quezon Province Beaches: A Calm Read Beyond Cagbalete',
        'slug' => 'quezon-province-beaches-calm-read-beyond-cagbalete',
        'excerpt' => 'Cagbalete gets most of the Quezon beach attention, but the province has several others worth the long drive. Here is the calm overview for first-timers.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Quezon Province has a coastline that stretches along both the Tayabas Bay on the west and the Lamon Bay on the east, with island clusters and small mainland coves spread across both sides. Cagbalete in Mauban gets most of the spotlight in Manila travel feeds, but the province also has Borawan in Padre Burgos, Kwebang Lampas in Pagbilao, Pulang Buli in Calauag, and a few more that reward the long drive. This is the calm overview for first-timers planning a Quezon beach weekend.</p>
<h2>How to Reach Quezon</h2>
<p>Most of the beach jump-offs are reached through Lucena City, the provincial capital. From Manila, take a <a href="https://www.jacliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">JAC Liner</a> or DLTB bus from Cubao or Buendia to Lucena Grand Terminal. The ride is around four hours. From Lucena, smaller vans, jeeps, or tricycles cover the local routes to the coastal towns.</p>
<h3>Driving Option</h3>
<p>If you drive, take SLEX to STAR Tollway, exit at Lucena, then follow the provincial roads to whichever beach you have chosen. Driving is the better option because the coastal jump-offs are spread out and the public transport connections can be slow.</p>
<h2>The Beach Options</h2>
<p>Pick one or two depending on how many nights you have. Most are two to four hours from Lucena, which makes them long weekend trips rather than day trips.</p>
<h3>Cagbalete Island in Mauban</h3>
<p>Cagbalete is the most famous of the Quezon beaches, a long stretch of fine white sand off the Mauban coast. The shallow tidal flats stretch hundreds of meters out at low tide, which is the landscape the photographers chase. Reached by a one-hour bangka from Mauban port. Two nights is the right length for the calm.</p>
<h3>Borawan Island in Padre Burgos</h3>
<p>Borawan is a small island that combines fine white sand with limestone outcrops, the name coming from a portmanteau of Boracay and Palawan. Day-trip accessible from Padre Burgos, or overnight at a small camp on the island itself. Pair with the Dampalitan and Puting Buhangin stops for a full island-hopping day.</p>
<h3>Kwebang Lampas in Pagbilao</h3>
<p>Kwebang Lampas, also called Puting Buhangin Beach, is a small white sand cove with a sea cave at the end. Reached by a short bangka from the Pagbilao mainland. Best as a half-day stop combined with the nearby Tikling Island.</p>
<h3>Anibawan Beach in Tagkawayan</h3>
<p>Anibawan is one of the quieter mainland beaches on the eastern side of the province, far from the more visited western shore. Pale sand and clear water, with no real infrastructure beyond a few homestays. Reached only with effort, around three hours from Lucena, which is exactly why it stays quiet.</p>
<h3>Cosme Beach in Atimonan</h3>
<p>Cosme is on the Lamon Bay side, a long stretch of gray sand backed by coconut groves. The town of Atimonan also has the Bantayan sa Hari watchtower from the Spanish era, which makes a nice pairing.</p>
<h2>The Standard Two-Night Plan</h2>
<p>For a first Quezon beach trip, the simplest plan is two nights at Cagbalete. The 90-minute boat ride is part of the experience, the island has enough simple lodges and beachfront pitches for tents, and the schedule of tides on the flats gives the days a rhythm.</p>
<h3>Day 1</h3>
<p>Arrive Mauban port by lunch, cross to Cagbalete on the afternoon bangka, settle into the lodge, walk the sandbar at low tide for sunset photos. Dinner is grilled fish and rice at the lodge kitchen.</p>
<h3>Day 2</h3>
<p>Slow morning swim, then a kayak around the western point, lunch back at the lodge, an afternoon walk to the longer northern beach, and sunset on the sandbar again. Optional bangka trip to neighboring Pandaraonan Island.</p>
<h3>Day 3</h3>
<p>Morning bangka back to Mauban, then bus or drive to Manila. Add a Lucban side trip for Kamay ni Hesus shrine and pancit habhab pasalubong if you have time.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Reef-safe sunscreen, a wide hat, and a rashguard</li>
    <li>Aqua shoes for the sandbar walk, the flats have small shells</li>
    <li>Dry bag for the bangka crossings</li>
    <li>Cash, the island lodges do not accept cards and the towns have limited ATMs</li>
    <li>Mosquito repellent for the dusk hours at the lodges</li>
    <li>Power bank, brownouts are common</li>
    <li>Trash bag, pack everything out from the islands</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from March to May give the calmest sea and the lowest tide schedules for the sandbar walks. The wet season from June to October can be rough on the eastern bay. Avoid typhoon weeks. The Pahiyas Festival in Lucban happens every May 15 and is worth pairing with a Cagbalete weekend.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay on the Mainland</h2>
<p>If you need an overnight in Lucena before or after the island leg, compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3437599-Lucena_Quezon_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Quezon Province has more beaches than the Manila feeds suggest. One slow long weekend is enough to learn the rhythm.</p>
