    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 19. Kamay ni Hesus + Lucban half-day
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2014/03/kamay-ni-hesus-shrine-in-lucban-quezon.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Kamay ni Hesus Shrine and Lucban Half-Day from Manila',
        'slug' => 'kamay-ni-hesus-shrine-lucban-half-day-manila',
        'excerpt' => 'Kamay ni Hesus Shrine in Lucban pairs naturally with the town heritage walk and a pancit habhab lunch. Here is the half-day plan from Manila.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Kamay ni Hesus Shrine sits on a hill at the edge of Lucban, Quezon, around three hours by road from Manila. The five-hectare complex includes the church where healing masses are celebrated, the Ascension Hill with its 305-step Via Dolorosa, and the Mary of the Risen Christ statue at the top of the hill. The shrine pairs naturally with a half-day in Lucban town, which sits at the foot of Mt. Banahaw and is famous for the Pahiyas Festival in May and for pancit habhab year round.</p>
<p>This is the calm half-day read.</p>
<h2>Getting to Lucban</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a <a href="https://www.jacliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">JAC Liner</a> bus from Cubao or Buendia to Lucena Grand Terminal. The ride is around four hours. From Lucena, transfer to a Lucban-bound jeepney or van at the terminal. The ride takes around 45 minutes through Tayabas and the foothills of Mt. Banahaw.</p>
<h3>Driving Option</h3>
<p>If you drive, the route is SLEX to STAR Tollway, exit at Lucena, then follow the provincial road through Tayabas to Lucban. Total drive time is around three hours in light traffic. The road from Tayabas climbs steadily through cool air and bamboo groves.</p>
<h3>Alternative Route via Laguna</h3>
<p>The other way in is through Laguna, passing Calamba, Los Banos, Bay, Victoria, Pila, Sta. Cruz, Pagsanjan, Cavinti, and Luisiana, then into Lucban. This route is slower but more scenic and pairs naturally with a Pagsanjan Falls stop if you want a full day.</p>
<h2>The Shrine Visit</h2>
<p>Kamay ni Hesus is on the outskirts of Lucban, around 10 minutes from the town center by tricycle. The standard visit takes around two hours including the climb and the church.</p>
<h3>The Ascension Hill Climb</h3>
<p>The 305 steps lead up to the Mary of the Risen Christ statue at the top of the hill. The Via Dolorosa stations line the climb, with concrete sculptures depicting the passion of Christ. Take it slowly because the steps are steep and the upper section has little shade. Bring water. The view at the top stretches across Lucban and toward Mt. Banahaw on clear days.</p>
<h3>The Church and the Healing Mass</h3>
<p>The church at the foot of the hill holds healing masses, usually on Wednesdays. The schedule changes, so check ahead through the shrine's social media. Even on non-mass days, the church is open for quiet prayer and the chapel of the Sacred Heart is worth visiting.</p>
<h3>The Garden Bookstore</h3>
<p>Next to the church is the garden and the small bookstore that sells religious items, prayer cards, and the local Lucban specialties. The bookstore proceeds support the shrine maintenance.</p>
<h2>Lucban Town Walk</h2>
<p>After the shrine, ride a tricycle back to the town center. The Lucban St. Louis Bishop of Toulouse Church faces the plaza and is one of the oldest in the province, dating to the 1600s. The plaza has the standard local stalls selling longganisang Lucban, pancit habhab, and the broomstick-shaped Lucban brooms.</p>
<h3>Lunch: Pancit Habhab</h3>
<p>Pancit habhab is the local specialty, a stir-fried noodle dish served on a banana leaf and eaten without utensils. The standard place is Buddy's Pancit Lucban or any of the small carinderias around the plaza. The longganisang Lucban is the savory pork sausage to order on the side.</p>
<h3>Pasalubong</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Longganisang Lucban, the local pork sausage</li>
    <li>Broas, the lady fingers used for trifles</li>
    <li>Lucban brooms, the broomstick-shaped soft brooms</li>
    <li>Apahap, the local steamed sweet rice cake</li>
    <li>Pancit habhab dry noodles for home cooking</li>
</ul>
<h2>If You Have the Full Day</h2>
<p>Add a stop at Kamay ni Hesus on the way in, eat at Lucban for lunch, then continue to the Casa Communidad de Tayabas heritage area in the afternoon. The Casa is a museum of Tayabas history. Alternative side trips include the Quezon National Park forest along the Atimonan road, or the Mt. Cristobal foothills for a quiet hike. For a longer trip, overnight in Lucban for the Saturday morning palengke.</p>
<h2>Where to Sleep</h2>
<p>Lucban has a handful of small inns and guesthouses for the overnight option. Most visitors do the shrine as a day trip from Manila or pair it with a Tagaytay or Pagsanjan overnight. You can compare Lucena options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3437599-Lucena_Quezon_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May are the most comfortable for the climb. The Pahiyas Festival on May 15 is the year's biggest event, with the houses decorated with kiping rice leaves and the whole town in a parade. The shrine itself can be very crowded during Holy Week and on weekends near a major feast day. Weekday visits are calmer.</p>
<p>One shrine, one heritage church, one banana-leaf lunch. The Lucban half-day pairs the spiritual stop with the small town walk Manila travelers underrate.</p>
