    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2014/04/beaches-near-manila-for-less-than-1000.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Budget Beaches Near Manila: Eight Calm Picks Under PHP 1,000',
        'slug' => 'budget-beaches-near-manila-eight-picks-under-1000',
        'excerpt' => 'A calm round-up of eight beaches reachable from Manila on a small budget. The bus fares, the side trips, and the realistic expectations for each.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Not every beach trip needs to be a flight and a resort. The Luzon coast has eight or so spots reachable from Manila by bus and bangka for a transit cost well under PHP 1,000 round trip per person, leaving the rest of the budget for food, camping fees, and small lodges. The catch is that all of these are simple, with limited infrastructure and minimal nightlife. This is the calm round-up for travelers willing to trade the polish for the savings.</p>
<h2>How the Math Works</h2>
<p>The PHP 1,000 figure assumes round-trip bus fare plus the bangka or jeepney transfer to the beach. It does not include food, lodging, or camping fees. Most of these beaches have basic homestay or camping options for low overnight rates, but a few are day trips only. Pack a sandwich, bring water, and accept that the cost-control depends on you.</p>
<h2>The Eight Picks</h2>
<h3>1. Nagsasa Cove, Zambales</h3>
<p>Around five hours by bus from Manila to San Antonio, then a bangka to the cove. Gray sand backed by agoho pines, perfect for tent camping with no resort and no Wi-Fi. The quieter alternative to Anawangin.</p>
<h3>2. Anawangin Cove, Zambales</h3>
<p>Same jump-off as Nagsasa but a shorter bangka ride. Busier on weekends and the trash situation has improved over the years. Still a good entry-level camping cove.</p>
<h3>3. Liwliwa Beach, Zambales</h3>
<p>The local surf community's quiet base in San Felipe. Gray sand, consistent waves from October to March, and a handful of small surf camps. Easier to reach than the coves because there is no bangka involved.</p>
<h3>4. Real, Quezon</h3>
<p>Reached by van from Cubao through the Sierra Madre to the Pacific side. Black sand beach with surf from October to February. Pair with Dingalan in Aurora or Polillo Island for a longer trip.</p>
<h3>5. Borawan Island, Quezon</h3>
<p>From Lucena, take a van to Padre Burgos and a bangka to Borawan. Small white sand cove with limestone outcrops. Day trip works, overnight on the island is rustic.</p>
<h3>6. Cagbalete Island, Mauban Quezon</h3>
<p>From Lucena, take a van to Mauban port, then a bangka to the island. Fine white sand and long tidal flats that stretch out at low tide. Two-night stay is the right length.</p>
<h3>7. Pundaquit Beach, Zambales</h3>
<p>The fishing village that serves as jump-off for Anawangin and Nagsasa. If you do not have time for the cove trips, the village beach itself is a calm sunset stop with Capones Island visible offshore.</p>
<h3>8. White Sand Beach in Bataan</h3>
<p>The Las Casas beach in Bagac, Bataan or the Mt. Samat side beaches like Five Fingers Cove. Reached by Genesis bus from Cubao to Balanga, then jeepney to the coastal towns. Day-trip or overnight options.</p>
<h2>What to Bring for Any of These</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Tent, sleeping mat, and a light blanket for camping</li>
    <li>Headlamp or flashlight</li>
    <li>Reef-safe sunscreen, a wide hat, and a rashguard</li>
    <li>Aqua shoes for rocky landings and tidal flats</li>
    <li>At least three liters of drinking water per person per day</li>
    <li>Cash in small bills, ATMs are limited near the jump-offs</li>
    <li>Trash bag, pack out everything you bring in</li>
    <li>Mosquito repellent for dusk</li>
    <li>Power bank, no outlets in camping setups</li>
</ul>
<h2>Bus Operators to Bookmark</h2>
<ul>
    <li><a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> for the Zambales coast routes</li>
    <li><a href="https://www.jacliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">JAC Liner</a> for the Lucena and Quezon routes</li>
    <li><a href="https://www.dltbco.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">DLTB Co.</a> for the southern Luzon coast</li>
    <li>Genesis Bus for the Bataan and Baler routes</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from November to May give the safest sea conditions. Avoid the typhoon weeks from August to October because the bangka services pause for safety. Weekends are busiest, especially long weekends like Labor Day and Independence Day. Weekday trips are calmer if your schedule allows.</p>
<h2>The Realistic Expectation</h2>
<p>These beaches are calm, simple, and sometimes basic. The tradeoff for the low budget is real. There is no air-conditioning in the tents. The toilets are pump-flush at best. The food is basic. What you get in return is a slower kind of trip, the kind where you walk the beach instead of refresh the Wi-Fi.</p>
<p>One sandwich, one bottle of sunscreen, one bus ticket. Eight beaches that prove a small budget can still get you to the sea.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Budget Beaches Near Manila Under PHP 1,000 | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm round-up of eight beaches reachable from Manila on a small budget. The bus and bangka routes, the side trips, and what to pack for each.',
        'tags' => 'budget beaches, Manila, Zambales, Quezon, weekend',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'manila',
