    // 21. Coron town proper
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2011/07/killing-some-time-in-coron-town-proper.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Coron Town Proper: What to Do on a Calm Non-Boat Day',
        'slug' => 'coron-town-proper-calm-non-boat-day-things-to-do',
        'excerpt' => 'Bad weather or a rest day in Coron does not mean a wasted day. Here is what to do in Coron town proper when the boats are not running.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Coron is mostly known for the island-hopping tours around Coron Island and Calamian Group. But the town proper on Busuanga has its own slow-day options when the weather grounds the boats, when you need a rest day in the middle of a longer trip, or when you simply want to skip another bangka and walk the town instead. The town is small enough to cover on foot in a single afternoon, with views of Coron Bay and the karst islands offshore.</p>
<p>This is the calm read for a non-boat day in town.</p>
<h2>Mount Tapyas at Sunset</h2>
<p>Mt. Tapyas is the hill that rises directly behind Coron town, marked by a large cross at the summit. The climb is around 700 steps, well maintained with handrails and viewing landings every 100 steps. From the top, the view stretches across Coron Bay to the karst peaks of Coron Island and the smaller surrounding islets. Sunset is the standard time to go, with the cross silhouetted against the western sky.</p>
<h3>The Climb</h3>
<p>Start the climb around an hour before sunset to give yourself time at the top. The lower steps are concrete, the upper steps a mix of concrete and natural stone. Bring a flashlight for the descent because the lights at the top go out at full dark. The steps can be slippery when wet, take it slow.</p>
<h2>Maquinit Hot Spring</h2>
<p>Maquinit Hot Spring sits around 10 minutes by tricycle from town, on the eastern side of Coron Bay. The pools are saltwater hot springs heated by the volcanic activity below. The water temperature is around 40 degrees Celsius, hot enough to require gradual entry. The spring is open until late evening, which makes it a calm closer for a non-boat day.</p>
<h3>What to Expect</h3>
<p>The setting is a mangrove area with three pools at different temperatures. Bring slippers, a towel, and a change of clothes. The entrance fee is collected at the gate. The pools are well maintained and the staff cleans regularly. Skip Maquinit if you have heart issues, the heat is real.</p>
<h2>Lualhati Park and the Waterfront</h2>
<p>Lualhati Park is the small public space along the Coron waterfront, with a view of the bay and the offshore islands. The park has benches, small food stalls, and a fishing pier. The locals gather here in the late afternoon. It is a good spot for a slow merienda and a snack of grilled corn or pansit miki.</p>
<h2>The Public Market and the Wet Side</h2>
<p>The Coron public market is a short walk from the waterfront. The wet side has fresh fish brought in daily by the fishermen, including talakitok, tuna, lapulapu, and several local species you may not recognize. Buy what you like and the small seafood restaurants nearby will cook it for you for a small fee. This is the cheapest way to eat fresh seafood in town.</p>
<h2>Calamianes Heritage Museum</h2>
<p>The small museum near the town center tells the story of the Calamian Tagbanwa people, the original inhabitants of the islands. The collection includes traditional crafts, photographs, and short historical narratives. The visit is short, around 45 minutes, but worth it for the cultural context behind the islands you have been touring.</p>
<h2>Coffee and Cafes</h2>
<p>The cafe scene in Coron town has grown over the years. Some of the names to try include Altrove Pizzeria for wood-fired pizza, Lolo Nonoy's for local Filipino plates, and Kawayanan for the calm garden setting. Most cafes have decent Wi-Fi if you need to catch up on messages or work emails.</p>
<h2>What to Buy as Pasalubong</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Cashew nuts from Busuanga, the local crop</li>
    <li>Dried seafood from the public market, pack carefully for the flight</li>
    <li>Cashew brittle and other coconut-based sweets</li>
    <li>Handwoven baskets and bags from the Calamian Tagbanwa community</li>
    <li>Local honey from the Busuanga apiaries</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Do If It Rains</h2>
<p>The wet season from June to October can bring full-day rain that grounds the boats. On these days, the cafe loops, the heritage museum, and the hot spring fill the time well. Some accommodations also have movie nights or board games for the longer rainy stretches.</p>
<h2>Getting Around Town</h2>
<p>The town is small enough to walk for most stops. For the hot spring and the farther viewpoints, take a tricycle from the public market. Settle the price before riding. Habal-habal motorcycles are also available for solo travelers.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Coron town has the densest accommodation cluster in the area, with options from hostels to mid-range hotels. You can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g664654-Coron_Busuanga_Island_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Staying in town gives easy access to the boat pier and the food.</p>
<p>Coron without the boats is still Coron. A climb, a hot spring, a market lunch, and a sunset bay walk. The town earns the rest day.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Coron Town Proper Things to Do on Non-Boat Days | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm guide to what to do in Coron town proper when the boats are not running. Mt. Tapsay, Maquinit Hot Spring, the public market, and the cafes.',
