    // 22. Bacolod to Iloilo ferry
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2022/09/bacolod-to-iloilo-ferry-schedule-fare.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Bacolod to Iloilo Ferry: A Calm Day-Crossing Read',
        'slug' => 'bacolod-to-iloilo-ferry-calm-day-crossing-read',
        'excerpt' => 'The Bacolod to Iloilo ferry is the calmest way to combine two Western Visayas cities in one trip. Here is the schedule, the ports, and what to do at each side.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Bacolod-to-Iloilo ferry crossing takes around an hour, runs every hour from early morning to late evening, and is the cleanest way to combine two of the major Western Visayas cities in a single trip. The route connects the Banago Port in Bacolod, Negros Occidental to the Iloilo Domestic Port across the Guimaras Strait. Both ends have decent terminal facilities, the boats are fast crafts with assigned seating, and the fare is low enough to make the crossing a casual half-day plan.</p>
<p>This is the calm read for travelers planning the city-to-city combo.</p>
<h2>The Ferry Itself</h2>
<p>The route is served by <a href="https://www.oceanjet.net" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">OceanJet</a>, Weesam Express, and FastCat. The hourly schedule runs from around 6 a.m. to 6 p.m. on both directions, with extra trips during peak season. Travel time is around one hour for the fast crafts, slightly longer for FastCat. The fast crafts have air-conditioned cabins with TVs, and the open deck is available for the breeze.</p>
<h3>Where to Book</h3>
<p>The smart move is to book online a day in advance, especially on weekends and holidays. Walk-in tickets are available at both ports, but the morning trips can fill up by 8 a.m. on busy days. Bring a printed ticket or a screenshot, the port staff scans the QR code.</p>
<h2>The Banago Port in Bacolod</h2>
<p>Banago Port is around 15 minutes from the Bacolod city center by Grab or taxi. Arrive at least 30 minutes before departure for the security check and the boarding queue. The terminal has basic food stalls and a waiting area with seats. There is no Wi-Fi at the port but cellular signal works.</p>
<h3>Bacolod Quick Stops</h3>
<p>If you have a half day in Bacolod before the crossing, the standard quick loop covers:</p>
<ul>
    <li>The Ruins in Talisay, the standout heritage stop just outside the city</li>
    <li>San Sebastian Cathedral and the Bacolod Public Plaza</li>
    <li>The Negros Museum for the city history</li>
    <li>Calea Pastries for the chocolate cake and the cheesecake</li>
    <li>Manokan Country for chicken inasal grilled over coconut husk</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Iloilo Domestic Port</h2>
<p>The Iloilo Domestic Port is around 20 minutes from the Iloilo city center by Grab or taxi. The terminal is newer than Banago and has more food options. The arrivals area exits directly to the taxi and Grab pickup zone.</p>
<h3>Iloilo Quick Stops</h3>
<p>If you have a half day in Iloilo after the crossing, the standard quick loop covers:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Calle Real, the heritage commercial street with Spanish-era buildings</li>
    <li>Molo Church for the all-female saint statues and the surrounding plaza</li>
    <li>La Paz Public Market for the original La Paz batchoy at Deco's or Netong's</li>
    <li>Miag-ao Church on the way south, a UNESCO World Heritage site</li>
    <li>Camina Balay nga Bato in Arevalo for the traditional Hiligaynon hot chocolate</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Combined Three-Day Plan</h2>
<p>The Bacolod-Iloilo combo works as a three-day trip with the ferry as the middle leg.</p>
<h3>Day 1: Bacolod</h3>
<p>Arrive Bacolod by morning flight, settle into hotel, do The Ruins and lunch at Bacolod public market, afternoon at the Negros Museum and the cathedral, dinner at Manokan Country.</p>
<h3>Day 2: Ferry and Iloilo</h3>
<p>Morning ferry to Iloilo, settle in, lunch at La Paz Public Market for the original batchoy, afternoon walking tour of Calle Real and Molo Church, dinner at one of the Smallville restaurants or at Camina Balay nga Bato for the heritage experience.</p>
<h3>Day 3: Guimaras or Miag-ao</h3>
<p>From Iloilo, take a 15-minute bangka to Jordan Wharf in Guimaras for the mango farm tour and Alubihod Beach, or drive south to Miag-ao Church and the nearby beaches. Return to Iloilo by late afternoon for the evening flight home.</p>
<h2>What to Bring for the Crossing</h2>
<ul>
    <li>A light jacket, the air-conditioning on the boat is strong</li>
    <li>A bottle of water and a small snack, the onboard food is basic</li>
    <li>Motion sickness pill if you are sensitive, the crossing is generally calm but the strait can get bumpy</li>
    <li>A dry bag for the open-deck breeze</li>
    <li>Cash for the terminal fees, the small charge at each port</li>
    <li>Government ID for the boarding queue</li>
</ul>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The dry months from December to May give the calmest crossings. The MassKara Festival in Bacolod is held every fourth weekend of October, and the Dinagyang Festival in Iloilo is the fourth weekend of January. Pair the ferry trip with one of these for the festival experience, but book hotels and ferry tickets well in advance because both cities fill up.</p>
<h2>Where to Sleep on Both Sides</h2>
<p>Both cities have a wide range of accommodation options. For Bacolod, compare on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298454-Bacolod_City_Negros_Occidental_Province_Western_Visayas_Region_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. For Iloilo, compare on the <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298453-Iloilo_City_Iloilo_Province_Panay_Island_Western_Visayas_Region_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Iloilo TripAdvisor PH page</a>. Pick the area near each city center for the walking loops.</p>
<p>One hour on a fast craft, two cities in one trip. The Bacolod-Iloilo combo earns the easy ferry seat.</p>
